5. a) ArrayList<Integer> grades = new ArrayList<Integer>();
int num = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++)
{
grades.add(0, num);
num++;
}
Output: [3, 2, 1, 0]

b) ArrayList<Integer> grades = new ArrayList<Integer>();
int num = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++)
{
grades.add(0, num);
num++;
}
//removes second index
grades.remove(2);
Output: [3, 2, 0]

6. When you pass the array to the method you are taking all the information contained in
the array while when you just pass an element, you're only taking a value from the array
and inputting it into the method. Also an array is passed as a reference data type while a single element passes the data stored not a reference to the data location.

7. An offset array can be used for instances like recording the output of a dice because it
allows the user to count from 1-6 instead of 0-5.

8. “i”
